olic Charities, and the Haitian Multi-Service Center: how social assistance produces and reproduces structural inequalities between providers and recipients; how these inequities may deepen aid recipients' dependence and lead to resistance to organized benevolence; how institutional financial deficits harmed clients and providers; and how the same modes of charity or philanthropy that previously caused harm can be redeployed to repair damage and rebuild "charitable brands." The culmination of more than a decade of advocacy and research on behalf of the Haitians in Boston, this groundbreaking work exposes how Catholic corporations have strengthened-but also eroded-Haitians' civic power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCatholic institutionszMassachusettszBoston. 0aChurch charitieszMassachusettszBoston. 0aChurch work with immigrantszMassachusettszBoston. 0aEqualityzMassachusettszBoston. 0aHaitian AmericansxServices forzMassachusettszBoston. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079135840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520400559zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520400559zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520400559/original  a978-3-11-079135-8 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA